commitResults.messageTitle: Move Address and PropertyAddress into separate package
commitResults.messageBody:
PropertyAddress is in the property package as it is a field in Property,
since it would not make sense to make use of the original Address
class in the person package. it is not named "Address" as well, since that
would mean conflicting class names in ParserUtil, where both classes
need to be imported.

however, since both PropertyAddress and Address have the same
implementation, it makes sense to have them as one class.

let's move both classes out to a separate address package. we then delete the
PropertyAddress class, and change all references to refer to the Address
class's new location in the address package instead.

there is only one file path ("addressbook.json") that stored the data of
the persons in the address book.

however, since we have two models, PersonModel and PropertyModel, we
need to have two JSON files to store each model.

let's rename addressBookFilePath to personModelFilePath to better
explain the JSON file's purpose, as well as its associated methods.
let's also add propertyModelFilePath, storing the PropertyModel in
"propertymodel.json".

let’s add getPropertyModelFilePath and setPropertyModelFilePath methods, while

Rename filter predicates and edit filter command javadocs
commitResults.messageBody:
Currently, we only have one type of predicate for filtering of
characteristics for each of property and buyer. the predicate checks
whether the buyer or property contains all the given characteristics
that the user is filtering by.

however, our matchprop and matchbuyer command will require a different
predicate that checks whether the buyer or property contains *any* of
the given characteristics.

thus, an initial clean up and refactoring of the files is done to
prevent confusion later on.

currently, matchprop only returns buyers that are within the price range
and matches all the characteristics of the property.

however, this might result in little to no buyers matched, as it is not
easy to satisfy this condition.

thus we loosen the criteria for a buyer to be matched in matchprop. a
buyer is matched if it is within the price range, OR contains at least
one of the property's characteristic.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add match all conditions ability in MultiFlagFilterBuyersCommand
commitResults.messageBody:
initially, MultiFlagFilterBuyersCommand will return buyers that satisfy
at least 1 of the specified conditions.

however, the user might only want buyers that satisfy all the given
conditions, especially if the list of buyers is very high.

let's add the ability to use the -all flag to specify whether we want
all the conditions to be present in the filtered buyers.

commitResults.messageTitle: Change fuzzy filtering behaviour for characteristics
commitResults.messageBody:
currently, if -fuzzy is passed in for the filter commands, the filtered
list will only contain buyers/properties that satisfy all the
characteristics, or at least one of the other conditions (e.g. price).

however, each characteristic should be seen as a condition by itself,
and thus the filtered list should also contain buyers/properties that
contain at least 1 but not all of the given characteristics.

commitResults.messageTitle: Allow application window to be resized
Require whitespace after flag when tokenizing args
commitResults.messageBody:
in AB3, the flag was in the format "<flag>/", thus the ArgumentTokenizer
only checked for a whitespace before the flag to recognise it as that
flag. this implementation was not changed when we changed the flag format to
"-<flag>". this continues to work, as long as we do not have flags that
had the same prefix (e.g. "-p" and "-ph"), in which case both "-ph" and "-p"
would be recognised as the "-p" prefix.

however, we recently standardised the flags in an effort to make it
consistent in all PRs. this resulted in the creation of the "-p" flag,
which is a prefix of the existing "-ph" flag, causing the above issue.

lets require a whitespace after the flag as well when tokenizing
arguments.

commitResults.messageBody:
updated test cases to reflect the error messages outputted by delete and
edit now. this is a flow of how the error message to be shown is
determined:

1. if no attempt to provide an index is present, invalid command format
   message is shown, telling the user the correct message usage.
2. if an attempt to provide an index is present but is incorrect (the
   index could be non-numeric as well), the wrong index message is
   shown.
3. for edit, if there was a valid index presented, but without any
   fields to edit, the at least one field message is shown.
